@book{Toret2008b,
abstract = {Endocytosis is a dynamic process that cells use to take up their plasma membrane. Many proteins that function in endocytosis are known, and an extensive network of protein interactions occurs between these endocytic proteins. As a result identifying where and how these endocytic proteins function in the endocytic pathway has been challenging. Live-cell imaging studies have shown that a precisely choreographed assembly of proteins occurs at endocytic sites in both budding yeast and mammals, but these studies have only examined a handful of the over 50 proteins that function in endocytosis. Here the effects of over 60 deletion mutants on the dynamics of the budding yeast endocytic pathway were studied, revealing functions for 20 proteins. In addition to the previously analyzed endocytic proteins, novel spatio-temporal dynamics were described for ∼35 proteins at endocytic sites, indicating that at least 50 proteins associate with endocytic sites. Analyzing deletion phenotypes and spatio-temporal dynamics of endocytic proteins provided evidence for four protein modules that cooperate to drive budding yeast endocytosis. These studies determined that budding yeast endocytosis is clathrin-mediated. Furthermore, actin polymerization at the plasma membrane was found to play an essential role in driving endocytic internalization. A critical role for yeast amphiphysins in facilitating vesicle scission was also discovered. Finally, a complex pathway was uncovered for regulating disassembly of the endocytic coat after internalization. Overall, these studies have yielded a comprehensive understanding of the events that occur during budding yeast endocytosis.},
